<P>Wite &thorn;e, <MILESTONE N="117, col. 2" UNIT="leaf">&slong;eli meiden!  Man &slong;ei&eth; &thorn;at
ei&slong;e make&eth; &thorn;eof. flih alle thinge&slong;, &amp;
forhuh &yogh;eorne, &thorn;at tus unbotelich lure of mahe
ari&slong;en; &thorn;at i&slong;, on alre ear&slong;t, &thorn;e
&slong;tude &amp; te time, &thorn;at mahten bringe &thorn;e on
mi&slong; for to donne.  Wi&eth; o&eth;re un&thorn;eawe&slong;, men
mai &slong;tondinde fehten; Ah a&yogh;ain leccherie, &thorn;u
mo&slong;t turne &thorn;e rug &yogh;if &thorn;u wult ouercumen, &amp;
wi&eth; fluht
 
<PB N="25">
fehten.  And &slong;o&eth;e&slong;, &yogh;if &thorn;u
&thorn;enche&slong; &amp; bihalde&slong;t on heh to-ward te muchele
mede &thorn;at meidenhad abide&eth;, &thorn;u wult lete lihtliche,
&amp; abeore bli&eth;eliche &thorn;e derf &thorn;at tu drehe&slong;t
onont ti fle&slong;chliche wil, &amp; ti licome&slong; lu&slong;t,
&thorn;at tu forbere&slong; her, & ane hwile leaue&slong;t, for
bli&slong;&slong;e &thorn;at cume&eth; &thorn;rof, wi&eth;uten ani
ende.
</P>
<P>And hwuch is te bli&slong;&slong;e?  low, godd him&slong;elf
&slong;ei&eth; &thorn;urh &thorn;e prophete: 
<Q>"&THORN;eo &thorn;at
habbi&eth; fram ham icoruen fle&slong;che&slong; lu&slong;tes, &amp;
halde&eth; mine &slong;abaz,"</Q> &thorn;at i&slong;, halden ham i
re&slong;te fram &thorn;at fle&slong;chliche werc, &amp; halden me
fore<MILESTONE N="117, back, col. 1" UNIT="leaf">ward, 
<Q>"Ich behate ham,"</Q> he &slong;ei&eth;, 
<Q>"i mi
kineriche to &yogh;iuen ham &slong;tude, &amp; betere nome &thorn;e[n]
&slong;unen &amp; dohtren."</Q> Hwa mihte wilni mare?  Eunuchus qui
&slong;eruauerit &slong;abbata mea &amp;c.  Hwa mei &thorn;enne<NOTE ID="n6"> ? for &thorn;enche</NOTE>&thorn;e weole, &thorn;e winne &amp; te bli&slong;&slong;e, &thorn;e
heh&slong;cipe of &thorn;e mede, &thorn;at ti&slong; ilke lut
worde&slong; bicluppen abuten?  
<Q>"Ichulle,"</Q> he &slong;ei&eth;,
<Q>"&yogh;eouen ham &slong;tude &amp; nome betere &thorn;en
&slong;unen & dohtren."</Q> &THORN;ulli bihea&slong;te; &amp; hit
i&slong; ilich &thorn;at &thorn;at ham i&slong; bihaten to
&slong;ingen wi&eth; engle&slong;, hwa&slong; felahe&slong; ha
beo&eth;, &thorn;urh liflade of heuene, &thorn;at &yogh;et &thorn;er
ha wune&eth; fle&slong;chliche on eor&eth;e. to &slong;inge &thorn;at
&slong;wote &slong;ong &amp; &thorn;at englene dream, ut-nume murie,
&thorn;at nane halwes ne mahen, bute meidene&slong; ane, &slong;ingen
in heuene; &amp; folhen godd almihti, euch godes ful, hwider &slong;e
he eauer wende&eth;, a&slong; &thorn;e o&eth;re ne mahen nawt,
&thorn;ah ha beon alle hi&slong;e &slong;unnen &amp; alle hi&slong;e
dehtren.  Ne nan of &thorn;e o&eth;re&slong; crunen, ne hare wlite, ne
hare weden, ne <MILESTONE N="117, col. 4" UNIT="leaf">mahen euenen to hare, &slong;e unimete brihte ha
beo&eth;, &amp; &slong;chene to bi&slong;eon on.
 
<PB N="27">
</P>
<P>And hwat be&eth; hare ane&slong; &slong;ong, &amp; after godd hare
ane&slong; gong, hwider-&slong;e he eauer turne&eth;?  and hare fare,
&slong;o feire biforen alle o&eth;re?  Vnder&slong;tond, &amp; nimy
&yogh;eme.  Al hare &slong;ong in heuene i&slong; for to &thorn;onki
godd of hi&slong; grace &amp; of hi&slong; goddede.  &THORN;e iweddede
&thorn;onken him &thorn;at, ha lauhure hwen ha alles walden fallen
duneward, ne fellen nawt wi&eth; alle adun, for wedlac ham ikepte,
&thorn;at ilke lahe &thorn;at godd haue&eth; i&slong;tald for &thorn;e
un&slong;tronge. for wel wi&slong;te ure lauerd, &thorn;at alle ne
mihten nawt halden i &thorn;e hehe of meidenhades mihte: ah
&slong;eide, &thorn;a he &slong;pec &thorn;rof, 
<Q>"Non omne&slong;
capiunt hoc uerbum: Ne underneome&eth; nawt,"</Q> quo&eth; he,
<Q>"&thorn;i&slong; ilke word alle.  Qui pote&slong;t capere, capiat.
Hwa&slong;e hit me underneomen, underneome, ich reade,"</Q> quo&eth;
he.  O&eth;er i&slong; &thorn;at godd hat; &amp; o&eth;er i&slong; tat
he reades.  &THORN;a ilke &thorn;inges &thorn;at he hat, &thorn;eo mot
mon <SIC>mot</SIC><MILESTONE N="118" UNIT="leaf"> nede halden, &thorn;at wile beon iburhen; &amp; &thorn;eo beon to
alle men o liue iliche meane: hi&slong; reade&slong; beo&eth; of heh
&thorn;ing, &amp; to hi&slong;e leoue&slong;te freond, &thorn;e lut i
&thorn;is worlde, &amp; derue beo&eth; to fullen, &amp; lihte
&thorn;ah hwa&slong;e haue&eth; riht luue to him, &amp; treowe
bileaue.  Ah hwa&slong;e halt &thorn;a, he earne&eth; him, ouerfullet,
ful & ouereorninde, met of heuenliche mede.  Swuch i&slong;
meidenhade&slong; read, &thorn;at godd ne hat nawt, ah read.  Hwuch-&slong;e wile beon of &thorn;e lut of hi&slong; leoue&slong;te freond,
&amp; a&slong; hi&slong; deore derling, don hi&slong; read, & earnin
him crune upo crune.  Al&slong;wa &slong;ente pawel &yogh;iue&eth;
read to meidenes, to beon as he was, &amp; sei&eth;, &thorn;at 
<Q>"wel
i&slong; ham &thorn;at &slong;wa ham mahen halden"</Q>; ne hat he hit
nan o&eth;re&slong; weis. for eauer fe deorre
 
<PB N="29">
&thorn;ing, &slong;e i&slong; derure to biwitene.  And &yogh;if hit
were ihaten, & nawt ta ihalden, &thorn;e bruche [were] deadliche
&slong;unne.
</P>
<P>For-&thorn;i was wedlac ilahet in hali chirche, <MILESTONE N="118, col. 2" UNIT="leaf">a&slong; bed to
&slong;eke, to ihente &thorn;e un&slong;tronge, &thorn;at ne mahten
nawt &slong;tonden in &thorn;e hehe hul, &amp; &slong;e neh heuene,
a&slong; meidenhades mihte.  &THORN;i&slong; i&slong;, tenne, hare
&slong;ong, &thorn;at beon i lahe of wedlac, &thorn;onki godd &amp;
herien, &thorn;at he grei&eth;ede ham, lanhure &thorn;a ha walden of
meidene&slong; heh&slong;cipe, a &slong;wuch &slong;tude in to lihten,
&thorn;at ha neren nawt ihurt, &thorn;ah ha weren ilahet, And hwat
&slong;e ha &thorn;rin hurten ham, wi&eth; ealmes deden healden.
&THORN;is &slong;inge&eth;, &thorn;enne, iweddede, &thorn;at ha,
&thorn;urh godes milce, &amp; merci of his grace, &thorn;a ha driuen
duneward, in wedlac at&slong;tutten, &amp; in &thorn;e bed of his lahe
&slong;ofteliche lihten.
</P>
<P>For hwa&slong;e &slong;wa falle&eth; of meidenhede&slong;
men&slong;ke, &thorn;at wedlake&slong; heueld bed nawt ham ne ihente,
&slong;e ferliche ha driuen dun to &thorn;e eor&eth;e, &thorn;at al
ham i&slong; tolimet li&eth; ba &amp; lire.  &THORN;eos ne
&slong;chulen neauer &slong;ong &slong;ingen in heuene, ah
&slong;chulen weimeres leod ai mare in helle, bute <MILESTONE N="118, back, col. 1" UNIT="leaf"> &yogh;if
bireow&slong;inge areare ham to liue, & heale ham wi&eth;
&slong;o&eth; &slong;chrift &amp; wi&eth; deadbote.
</P>
<P>For &yogh;if ha beo&eth; acwiket &amp; imaket hale, ha beo&eth; i
widewene ring, &amp; &slong;chulen, i widewene ring, bifore &thorn;e
iweddede &slong;ingen in heuene: &thorn;at i&slong;, tenne, hare
&slong;ong, to herien hare drihtin, & &thorn;onken him &yogh;eorne
&thorn;at hi&slong; mihte held ham i clean&slong;chipe cha&slong;te,
after &thorn;at ha hefden ifondet fle&slong;ehc&slong; ful&eth;e, &
&yogh;ettede ham i &thorn;i&slong; world to bete hare &slong;unnen.
Swote beo&eth;
 
<PB N="31">
&thorn;eos &slong;onge&slong;.  Ah al i&slong; meidene&slong;
&slong;ong unilich &thorn;eo&slong;e, wi&eth; engle&slong; imeane:
dream ouer al &thorn;e dreame&slong; in heuene.  In heore ring
&thorn;er [i&slong;] godd &slong;elf; &amp; hi&slong; deore moder,
&thorn;e deorewur&eth;e meiden, &thorn;e heuenliche cwen, leat i
&thorn;at eadi trume of &slong;chimerinde meidene&slong;: ne moten
nane bute heo hoppen ne &slong;ingen, for &thorn;at i&slong; ai hare
&slong;ong, &thorn;onken godd, &amp; herien, &thorn;at he on ham
&slong;e muche grace &yogh;ef of him &slong;eluen, &thorn;at ha
for&slong;oken for him euch eor&eth;lich mon, &amp; helden ham <MILESTONE N="118, back, col. 2" UNIT="leaf">cleane
ai fra fle&slong;chliche ful&eth;en i bodi &amp; i breo&slong;te;
&amp; i &slong;tude of mon of lam, token liues lauerd, &thorn;e king
of &thorn;e hehe bli&slong;&slong;e; for hwi he men&slong;ke&eth; ham
&slong;e muchel biforen alle &thorn;e o&eth;re, as te brudgume de&eth;
hi&slong; weddede &slong;puse.  &THORN;i&slong; &slong;ong, ne mahen
nane bute heo &slong;ingen.
</P>
<P>Alle, a&slong; ich &slong;eide ear, folhen ure lauerd, &amp; tah
nawt ouer al; for, i &thorn;e men&slong;ke of meiden[had] &amp; in
hire mihte, ne muhe nane folhen him, ne &thorn;at eadi meiden, englene
lafdi, &amp; meidene&slong; men&slong;ke, bute meidene&slong; ane.
And for-&thorn;i i&slong; hare aturn &slong;e briht &amp; &slong;e
&slong;chene biforen alle o&eth;re, &thorn;at ha Ga&eth; eauer
ne&slong;t godd, hwider&slong;e he turne&eth;.  And alle ha beo&eth;
icruned &thorn;at bli&slong;&slong;ed in heuene, wi&eth; kempene
crune.  Ah &thorn;e meidene&slong; habben upo &thorn;at, &thorn;at
i&slong; to alle iliche imeane, a gerlaunde&slong;che &slong;chinende
&slong;chenre &thorn;en &thorn;e &slong;unne: `Auriole' ihaten o
latine&slong; ledene.  &THORN;e flur&slong; &thorn;at beo&eth; idrahe
&thorn;ron, ne &thorn;e &yogh;im&slong;tanes <MILESTONE N="119" UNIT="leaf">&thorn;rin, te tellen of
hare euene, ne i&slong; na monne&slong; &slong;peche.  &THORN;us feole
priuilege&slong; &slong;cheawe&eth; ful &slong;utelliche hwucche beon
&thorn;e meidne&slong;, &amp; &slong;undre&eth; ham fram &thorn;e
o&eth;re wi&eth; &thorn;us feole men&slong;ken, world buten ende.
 
<PB N="33">
</P>
<P>Of &thorn;eos &thorn;re had, meidenhad &amp; widewehad, &amp; te
&thorn;ridde, wedlachad, &thorn;u maht, bi &thorn;e degrez of hare
bli&slong;&slong;e, icnawen hwuch, &amp; bi hu muchel, &thorn;e an
pa&slong;&slong;e&eth; &thorn;e o&eth;re. for wedlac haue&eth; hire
frut &thorn;ritti-fald in heuene; widewehad, &slong;ixti fald;
Maidenhad, wi&eth; hundred fald, ouer-Gea&eth; ba&eth;e.  loke,
&thorn;enne, her-bi, hwa &slong;e of hire maidenhad lihte&eth; in-to
wedlac, bi hu moni degrez ha falle&eth; duneward.  Ha is an hundred
degrez ihehet toward heuene, hwil ha meidenhad halt, a&slong;
&thorn;at frut preoue&eth;; &amp; leape&eth; in-to wedlac, &thorn;at
i&slong; duneward to &thorn;e &thorn;rittu&eth;e, ouer &thorn;rie
twenti &amp; &yogh;et ma bi tene. ni&slong; ti&slong;, at an chere, a
muche lupe duneward?  &amp; tah hit i&slong; <MILESTONE N="119, col. 2" UNIT="leaf">to &thorn;olien.  And
godd haue&eth; ilahed hit, as ich ear &slong;eide, le&slong;te hwa
&slong;e leope, &amp; tenne lauhure nawt nere hwat kep to [read kepte]
him, &amp; driue adun &slong;wirefor&eth;, wi&eth;uten ikepunge, deope
in-to helle.  Of &thorn;eos nis nawt to &slong;peken, for ha beo&eth;
i&slong;crepte ut of liues writ in heuene.
</P>
<P>&para;Ah &slong;cheawe witerluker, as we ear biheten, hwat drehen
&thorn;e iweddede, &thorn;at tu icnawe &thorn;erbi hu murie &thorn;u
maht liuen, meiden i &thorn;i meidenhad, ouer &thorn;at heo libben,
teke &thorn;e murh&eth;e &amp; te men&slong;ke in heuene, &thorn;at
mu&eth; ne mai nummnen.  Nu &thorn;u art iwedded, &amp; of &slong;e
heh &slong;e lahe iliht,&mdash;of englene ilicne&slong;&slong;e, of
ihesu cri&slong;te&slong; leofmon, of leafdi in heuene,&mdash;in-to
fle&slong;che&slong; ful&eth;e, in-to bea&slong;te&slong; liflade,
in-to monne&slong; &thorn;eowdom, &amp; in to worldes weane.  &YOGH;ei
nu, hwat frut, &amp; for hwuch &thorn;ing mea&slong;t hit is: al for
&thorn;i, o&eth;er ane deale &thorn;er fore. beo nu &slong;o&eth;
 
<PB N="35">
cnawe&slong;, for to kele &thorn;i lu&slong;t wi&eth; ful&eth;e of
&thorn;i lico<MILESTONE N="119, back, col. 4" UNIT="leaf"> me, for to habbe delit of &thorn;i fle&slong;chliche
wil of monne&slong; imeane; for gode, hit i&slong; wlateful &thorn;ing
for te &thorn;enke &thorn;ron; &amp; for to &slong;peke &thorn;er-of,
&yogh;et wlatefulre. loke, &thorn;enne, hw[u]ch beo &thorn;at
&slong;elue &thorn;ing, &amp; &thorn;at dede to donne.  Al &thorn;at
fule delit i&slong; wi&eth; ful&eth;e aleid, a&slong; tu turne&slong;t
&thorn;in hond.  Ah &thorn;at la&eth;liche bea&slong;t leaue&eth;
&amp; la&slong;t for&eth;; And te of-&thorn;unchinge &thorn;rof longe
&thorn;er-after.  <NOTE ID="n7"> Rubbed out in Titus MS., supplied from Bodley.</NOTE>[Ant te unseli horlin]ges &thorn;at unlaheliche hit
haunte&eth; in inwarde helle: for &thorn;at hwilende lu&slong;t,
endele&slong; pine, bute &yogh;if ha hit leauen, &amp; hit on
eor&eth;e under &slong;chrift bitterliche beten. forhohe for to don
hit &thorn;at te &thorn;unche&eth; uuel of, &amp; eil for to
heren. for hwen hit i&slong; &thorn;ullich, &amp; muche dale
la&eth;luker &thorn;en eni wel-itohe mu&eth; for &slong;chome mahe
&slong;eggen, hwat make&eth; hit iluued bituhhe bea&slong;tliche men,
bute hare muchele un&thorn;eaw, &thorn;at bere&eth; a&slong;
bea&slong;te&slong; to al &thorn;at ham lu&slong;te&eth;, as tah ha
nefden wit in ham ne <MILESTONE N="119, back, col. 4" UNIT="leaf">tweire schead as mon haue&eth;, ba of god &amp;
of uuel, of cumelich &amp; of uncumelich, na mare &thorn;en
bea&slong;tes, &thorn;at dumbe neb habbe&eth;.  Ah, lea&slong;&slong;e
&thorn;en bea&slong;tes &yogh;et; for &thorn;eos do&eth; hare cunde
(wi&eth;ute wit &thorn;ah ha beon) in a time of &thorn;e &yogh;er.
Moni halt him til an make, ne nule after &thorn;at lure neauer nimen
o&eth;er.  And mon &thorn;at &slong;chulde haue wit, &amp; do al
&thorn;at he dude after hire wi&slong;&slong;inge, folhe&eth;
&thorn;at ful&eth;e in eauer-euch time; &amp; nime&eth; an after an,
&amp; monie &thorn;at i&slong; wur&slong;e, monie to-Gedere&slong;.
</P>
<P>Loke hu &thorn;i&slong; un&thorn;eaw ne euene&eth; &thorn;e, nawt
ane to witle&slong;e bea&slong;tes dumbe &amp; broke-rugget, ibuhe
