&amp; te cheorl chide&eth;.  &THORN;ah hit be egede &slong;ahe, hit
ah, meiden, to eggi &thorn;e &slong;wi&eth;re &thorn;erframward, for
nawt ne &thorn;unche hit hire egede &thorn;at hit fonde&eth;.  Ne
&thorn;arf &thorn;at &slong;eli meiden &thorn;at haue&eth; al idon hire
ut of &thorn;ullich &thorn;eowdom, a&slong;e godes fre dohter, &amp; <MILESTONE N="123, back, col. 2" UNIT="leaf">
his &slong;unes &slong;puse, drehe nawt &slong;wucches. for&thorn;i,
&slong;eli meiden, for&slong;ac al &thorn;ullich &slong;orhe for
utnume mede, &thorn;at tu ahe&slong; to don wi&eth;uten euch huire.
 
<PB N="55">
</P>
<P>Nu ich habbe ihalden mine bihea&slong;te &thorn;ruppe: &thorn;at
ich walde &slong;cheawen wi&eth; fal&slong;chipe i&slong;me&eth;et,
&thorn;at te moni an &slong;ei&eth; & &thorn;unche&eth; &thorn;at hit
&slong;o&eth; beo, of &thorn;e &slong;elh&eth;e &amp; te &slong;wete
&thorn;at te iweddede habben; &thorn;at hit ne fare&eth; nawt
&slong;wa, as wene&eth; &thorn;at i&slong;eo&eth; utewi&eth;; ah
fare&eth; al o&eth;er weis, of poure ba &amp; riche, of la&eth;e &amp;
ec of leouie; &thorn;at te weane eihwer pa&slong;&slong;e&eth;
&thorn;e winne, &amp; te lure ouer al, al &thorn;e bi&yogh;eate.
</P>
<P>Nu, &thorn;enne, &slong;eli meiden, &thorn;at daui&eth; cleope&eth;
<Q>"dohter,"</Q> Iher &thorn;i fader," &amp; hercne his read, &thorn;at
he i &thorn;e frum&eth;e of &thorn;is writ readde: 
<Q>"for&yogh;et ti
folc"</Q> &thorn;at lihe&eth; &thorn;e of weres &amp; worldes wunne
;&mdash;&thorn;at beo&eth; &thorn;ine &thorn;ohtes, &thorn;at
&slong;wikeliche leade&eth; &thorn;e toward alle weane ;&mdash;
<Q>"&
for&slong;ac &thorn;i fader hus,"</Q> as hit is &thorn;er-uppe
iopenet, &amp; tac &thorn;e to him treowliche. wi&eth; him &thorn;u
&slong;chalt wealden, as wi&eth; &thorn;i were iwedded, world <MILESTONE N="124" UNIT="leaf">buten
ende, heuenriche winnen.  Eadi i&slong; his &slong;puse, hwas
meidenhad i&slong; unwemmed, hwen he on hire &slong;treone&eth;; &amp;
hwen ha teame&eth; of him, ne &slong;winke&eth; ne ne pine&eth;.  Eadi
i&slong; te were hwen nan ne mei beo meiden bute &yogh;if ha him
luuie, ne freo bute &yogh;if ha him &slong;erui; Hwa&slong;
&slong;treon i&slong; undeadlich, &amp; hwas marhe-&yogh;iue i&slong;
te kinedom of heuene.  Nu, &thorn;enne, &slong;eli meiden, &yogh;if
&thorn;e is weole leof, nim &thorn;e him to lauerd, &thorn;at
wealde&eth; al &thorn;at is, &amp; was, & eauer &slong;chal
iwur&eth;en; for &thorn;ah he beo riche&slong;t, him ane, ouer alle,
&thorn;e alre mea&slong;t poure &thorn;at him to were
cheo&slong;e&eth;, is him wel icweme.
 
<PB N="57">
</P>
<P>&YOGH;if &thorn;at tu wilne&slong;t were &thorn;at muche wlite
habbe, nim him of hwas wlite beo&eth; awundret &thorn;e &slong;unne
&amp; te mone, upo hwas neb&slong;chaft &thorn;e engles ne beo&eth;
neauer fulle to bihalden; for, hwen he &yogh;iue&eth; feirlec to al
&thorn;at is feir in heuene &amp; in eor&eth;e, muche mare he
haue&eth;, wi&eth;uten eni etlunge, at-halden to him &slong;eluen; &
tah hwen <MILESTONE N="124, col. 2" UNIT="leaf">he &thorn;us is alre &thorn;inge feirest, he vnderfe&eth;
bli&eth;eliche, &amp; bicluppe&eth; &slong;woteluche, &thorn;e alre
la&eth;luke&slong;t, & make&eth; ham &slong;eoue&slong;i&eth;e
&slong;chenre &thorn;en &thorn;e &slong;unne.
</P>
<P>&YOGH;if &thorn;e were &slong;treon leof, nim &thorn;e to him,
under hwam &thorn;u &slong;chalt, i &thorn;i meidenhad, teamen dohtren
&amp; &slong;unen of ga&slong;tliche teames, &thorn;at neauer ne
deiene mahen, ah &slong;chulen ai bifore &thorn;e pleien in heuene;
&thorn;at beon, &thorn;e uertuz &thorn;at he &slong;treone&eth; in
&thorn;e &thorn;urh his &slong;wete grace, As
rihtwi&slong;ne&slong;&slong;e &amp; war&slong;chipe a&yogh;aines
un&thorn;eawes; Me&slong;ure &amp; mete, &amp; ea&slong;tliche
&slong;treng&eth;e to wi&eth;&slong;tonde &thorn;e feond, &amp;
a&yogh;ain &slong;unne; Simplete of &slong;emblaunt, &amp;
buh&slong;umne&slong;&slong;e &amp; &slong;til&eth;e,
&thorn;olemodne&slong;&slong;e & reowfulne&slong;&slong;e of euch
monnes &slong;orhe; Glad&slong;chipe i &thorn;e hali ga&slong;t, &amp;
pes i &thorn;i breo&slong;te of onde &amp; of wra&eth;&eth;e, of
&yogh;i&slong;cinge &amp; of euch un&thorn;eawes worre; Mekelec &amp;
mild&slong;chipe, & &slong;wotne&slong;&slong;e of heorte, &thorn;at
limpe&eth; alre &thorn;inge be&slong;t to meidenhades mihte. &thorn;is
is <MILESTONE N="124, back" UNIT="leaf">meidenes team, godes &slong;unes &slong;puse, &thorn;at
&slong;chal hire ai libben &amp; pleien buten ende bifore hire in
heuene.
</P>
<P>&para; Ah &thorn;ah &thorn;u, meiden, beo wi&eth;ute bruche of
&thorn;i bodi, &amp; tu habbe prude, onde, o&eth;er wra&eth;&eth;e,
&yogh;i&slong;cinge, o&eth;er wac wil, inwi&eth; i &thorn;in heorte,
&thorn;u forhore&slong; te wi&eth; &thorn;e unwiht of helle, &amp; he
&slong;treone&eth; on &thorn;e &thorn;e teames
 
<PB N="59">
&thorn;at tu teame&slong;t.  Hwen &thorn;i were, al wealdent,
&thorn;at tu &thorn;e to wedde&slong;t, &slong;e&eth; &amp;
under&slong;tond tis, &thorn;at his fa forli&eth; &thorn;e, &
&thorn;at tu teame&slong;t of him &thorn;at him i&slong; teame
la&eth;e&slong;t, He forhohe&eth; &thorn;e anan&mdash;as hit nis na
wunder&mdash; &amp; cwe&eth;e&eth; &thorn;e al cwite him &thorn;at tu
of teame&slong;t; ne kepe&eth; he wi&eth; na mon, & hure wi&eth; his
famon, na half dale. hwa &thorn;at luue&eth; eawiht bute him, &amp;
hwat-&slong;e ha for him ne luue&eth;, ha wra&eth;&eth;e&eth; him
&slong;wi&eth;e.
</P>
<P>Ouer alle &thorn;ing, wite <MILESTONE N="124, back, col. 2" UNIT="leaf">&thorn;e &thorn;at tu ne teami prude bi
&thorn;e deoule&slong; &slong;treonunge, for heo, of alle
un&thorn;eawes, i&slong; his ealde&slong;te dohter.  Earst ha wakenede
of him &thorn;a &yogh;et &thorn;a he wes in heuene, for neh wi&eth;
him euen hald; &amp; &slong;wa ha ca&slong;t hire fader, &slong;one
&slong;e ha iboren wes, fram &thorn;e heh&slong;te heuene in-to helle
grunde wi&eth;ute couerunge, &amp; makede of heh engel,
eateluke&slong;t deouel.  Heo &thorn;at tus adu&slong;te hire
heuenliche fader adun, hwat wile ha don bi hire eor&eth;liche modres,
&thorn;at teame&eth; hire in horedom of &thorn;en la&eth;e vnwiht,
&thorn;e hellene fchucke.  Hwen Godd &slong;e wracfulliche fordemde
his heh engel &thorn;at &slong;treonede hire in heuene, hwat wile he
don bi &thorn;at lam, &amp; wurmene mete, &thorn;at of &thorn;e deouol
teame&eth; hire on eor&eth;e?
</P>
<P>&YOGH;if &thorn;u haues, wi&eth; meidenhad, meokelec &amp;
mild&slong;chipe, godd is <MILESTONE N="125" UNIT="leaf">i &thorn;in heorte.  Ah &yogh;if &thorn;er
is ouerhohe o&eth;er eni prude in, he is utlahe &thorn;rof; for ne
muhen ha nanes weis bedden in a breo&slong;te; ha ne muhen nawt
&slong;omen earden in heuene. &thorn;eone godd warp hire, &slong;one
&slong;e ha [iboren wes; &amp; as ha nuste hwuch wei ha<NOTE ID="n10"> From Bodley MS.</NOTE>] come
&thorn;eneward, ne con ha neauer mare ifinden na wei a&yogh;ainward.
Ah eardinde her on eor&eth;e, bihat
 
<PB N="61">
eche wununge alle hire modres, al beon ha meidne&slong;, wi&eth; hare
awariede fader in inwarde helle.  Wite &thorn;e, meiden, wi&eth; hire!
Ha cwikede of cleane cunde, a&slong; i&slong; in engle&slong; euene,
&amp; clenne&slong;te bre&slong;ten brede&eth; hire <MILESTONE N="125, col. 2" UNIT="leaf"> &yogh;ette.
&THORN;e be&slong;te ha a&slong;a&yogh;ile&eth;; & wel ha dar hopien
to beo kempe ouer mon, &thorn;at ouercom engel.  Nis ha nawt in
cla&eth;es, ne in feahunge utewi&eth;, &thorn;ah hit beo merke
&thorn;rof, &amp; munegunge o&eth;er hwiles; Ah under hwit o&eth;er
blac, &amp; a&slong;e wel vnder grei, as under Grene &amp; gra, ha
lute&eth; i &thorn;e heorte.  Sone &slong;o &thorn;u telles te betere
&thorn;en an o&eth;er&mdash;beo hit hwer-fore &slong;e hit eauer
beo,&mdash;&amp; haue&slong;t of eni ouerhohe, &amp; &thorn;unche&eth;
hofles & hoker of ewt &thorn;at mon &slong;ei&eth; &thorn;e o&eth;er
de&eth; &yogh;ette, &thorn;u marres ti meidenhad, &amp; brekes ti
wedlac toward godd, &amp; of his fa temes.
</P>
<P><MILESTONE N="125, back" UNIT="leaf"> Ne telle &thorn;u nawt e&eth;elich, al beo &thorn;u meiden, to
widewen ne to iweddede; for, al&slong;wa as a charbucle i&slong;
betere &thorn;en a iacinct i &thorn;e euene of hare cunde, &amp; tah
is betere a briht iacinct &thorn;en a charbucle won, Al&slong;wa
pa&slong;&slong;e&eth; meiden, onont te mihte of meidenhad, widewen
&amp; iweddede; &amp; tah is betere, a milde wif o&eth;er a meoke
widewe, &thorn;en a prud meiden; for &thorn;eos, for hore &slong;unnen
&thorn;at ha i fle&slong;ches ful&eth;e folhen, leoten ham lahe &amp;
e&eth;eliche, &amp; beo&eth; &slong;are offeared of godes lu&eth;ere
eie; And as te eadi &slong;unegild marie Magdalene, wi&eth; bittre
wopes, bireow&slong;e&eth; hare gultes, & inwardluke&slong;t
luuie&eth; godd, al&slong;wa as heo dide, for hare
for&yogh;eouene&slong;&slong;e; <MILESTONE N="125, back, col. 2" UNIT="leaf">And te o&eth;re &thorn;at halden ham
vnforgult & cleane, beon a&slong;e &slong;ikere unlu&slong;tie &amp;
wlecche, liue&eth; i godes luue,
 
<PB N="63">
wi&eth;uten euch heate of &thorn;e hali ga&slong;t, &thorn;at
bearne&eth; &slong;e lihte, wi&eth;ute wa&slong;tinde brune in alle
hi&slong;e icorene; And te o&eth;re, in a heate of an hondhwile, beon
imealt mare &amp; i&yogh;otten in godd, &thorn;en &thorn;e o&eth;re in
a wlecchunge al hare lif&slong;i&eth;e.
</P>
<P>For&thorn;i, eadi meiden, gode&slong; &slong;une &slong;puse, ne
beo &thorn;u nawt to tru&slong;ti ane to &thorn;i meidenhad,
wi&eth;uten o&eth;er God &amp; &thorn;awfule mihtes, &amp; ouer al,
milt&slong;chipe &amp; meoke&slong;chipe of heorte, after &thorn;e
bisne of &thorn;at eadi meiden ouer all o&eth;re, marie, godes
moder. for, &thorn;a &thorn;e hehe engel Gabriel grette hire, &amp;
brohte hire &thorn;e tidinge of godes akenne&slong;&slong;e, loke hu
lah ha <MILESTONE N="126" UNIT="leaf"> lette hire, &thorn;a ha on&slong;werede &thorn;us bi hire
&slong;elue: 
<Q>"low, her mi lauerdes &thorn;ralle!  After &thorn;i
word,"</Q> quo&eth; ha, 
<Q>"mote me iwur&eth;en!"</Q> And tah ha ful
were of alle gode &thorn;eawes, hane of hire mekelec ha &slong;eide &
&slong;ong to Helizabeth: 
<Q>"for mi lauerd bi&slong;eh his
&thorn;ufftenes mekelac, me &slong;chulen clepien,"</Q> quo&eth; ha,
<Q>"eadi, alle leoden."</Q> Nim &yogh;eme, meiden, &amp;
under&slong;tond herbi, &thorn;at mare for hire mekelec &thorn;en for
hire meidenhad, ha lette &thorn;at ha ifond &slong;wuch grace a&eth;
ure lauerd. for al meidenhad, mekelec is muche wur&eth;; & meidenhad
wi&eth;uten hit is e&eth;eliche &amp; unwur&eth;; for al &slong;wa is
meiden i meidenhad, wi&eth;ute mekelec, as is, wi&eth;ute liht, eoile
in a laumpe.  Eadi gode&slong; &slong;puse !  haue &thorn;is ilke
mihte, &thorn;at tu ne &thorn;unche &thorn;eo&slong;tri, ah
&slong;chine as te &slong;unne i &thorn;i weres &slong;ih&eth;e. feahe
&thorn;i meidenhad wi&eth; alle gode &thorn;eawes, &thorn;at
&thorn;unche&eth; him feire.
</P>
<P>Haue eauer i &thorn;in herte &thorn;e eadie&slong;te of meidnes,
&amp; <MILESTONE N="126, col. 2" UNIT="leaf">meidenhades mo&eth;er; &amp; bi&slong;ech ai hire &thorn;at ha
&thorn;e lihte, &amp; &yogh;iue luue & &slong;treng&eth;e for
 
<PB N="65">
to folhe in meidenhad hire &thorn;eawes.  &THORN;ench o Seint
Katerine, o Margarete, Enneis, Iuliene, Lucie, Cecille ; &amp; o
&thorn;e o&eth;re hali meidnes in heuene; Hu ha nawt ane
for&slong;oken kinge&slong; &slong;unnes & eorles, wi&eth; alle
worldliche weolen &amp; eor&eth;liche wunnen, Ah &thorn;oleden
&slong;tronge pines ear ha walden nimen ham, &amp; derf dea&eth; on
ende.  &THORN;ench hu wel ham is nu, &amp; hu ha
bli&slong;&slong;e&eth; &thorn;erfore bituhhe godes arme&slong;,
cwenes of heuene!  And &yogh;if hit eauer time&eth; &thorn;at ti
licome&slong; lu&slong;t, &thorn;urh &thorn;e fal&slong;e feond,
leade&eth; &thorn;e toward fle&slong;chliche ful&eth;e, on&slong;were
i &thorn;i &thorn;oht tus: `Ne Geine&eth; &thorn;e nawt, &slong;weoke!
&thorn;ullich ichulle beon i meidenes liflade, Ilich heuene engel.
Ichulle halde me hal, <MILESTONE N="126, back" UNIT="leaf">&thorn;urh &thorn;e grace of godd, a&slong;
cunde me makede, &thorn;at parai&slong;e &slong;elh&eth;e underfo me,
all &slong;wuch a&slong; weren, ear ha Gulten, his ear&slong;te
heamen.  Allunge, &slong;wuch ichulle beon as i&slong; mi deore
leofmon, mi derewur&eth;e lauerd, &amp; as i&slong; tat eadi meiden
&thorn;at he him chea&slong; to moder.  Al &slong;wuch ichulle wite
me, treoweliche unwemmet, a&slong; ich am him iweddet. ne nul ich
nawt, for a lu&slong;t of a lute hwile, &thorn;ah hit &thorn;unche
delit, awai warpe &thorn;at &thorn;ing, hwas lure ichulle biremen
wi&eth;ute couerunge, & wi&eth; eche brune abuggen in helle. &thorn;u
wrech-wile-ful wiht!  al for nawt &thorn;u proke&slong;t me to
forgulten, &amp; forgan &thorn;e bli&slong;&slong;e up-o
bli&slong;&slong;e, &thorn;e crune up-o crune of meidene&slong; mede;
&amp; willes & waldes warpe me as wrecche i &thorn;i leirwite; And,
for &thorn;at englene &slong;ong <MILESTONE N="126, back, col. 2" UNIT="leaf">of meidenhades men&slong;ke, wi&eth;
&thorn;e &amp; wi&eth; &thorn;ine greden ai & granen i &thorn;e eche
grure of helle.'
 
<PB N="67">
</P>
<P>&YOGH;if &thorn;u &thorn;us on&slong;weres to &thorn;i licomes
lu&slong;t &amp; to &thorn;e feondes fondinge, he &slong;chal fleo
&thorn;e wi&eth; &slong;chome.  And &yogh;if he alles after &thorn;is,
inoh ra&eth;e, at&slong;tonde &amp; halt on to eili &thorn;i
fle&slong;ch &amp; prokie &thorn;in herte, &thorn;i lauerd godd hit
&thorn;ole&eth; him to muccli &thorn;i mede; for, as &slong;ente pawel
&slong;ei&eth;, `ne be&eth; nan icrunet, bute hwa&slong;e treoweliche
i &thorn;ulli feht fihte, &amp; wi&eth; &slong;trong cockunge ouercume
hire fle&slong;ch'; for &thorn;enne i&slong; te deouel, wi&eth;
hi&slong; ahne turn, &slong;chomeliche awarpen.  Hwen &thorn;u,
a&slong; te apo&slong;tle &slong;ei&eth;, ne &slong;chalt beon
icrunet, bute &thorn;u beo a&slong;ail&yogh;et; for [&yogh;if] godd <MILESTONE N="127" UNIT="leaf">
wile cruni &thorn;e, he wile leote ful wel &thorn;e unwiht
a&slong;ail&yogh;e &thorn;e, &thorn;at tu earni &thorn;er-&thorn;urh,
crune upo crune. for-&thorn;i hit i&slong; &thorn;e mea&slong;t god,
&thorn;at, hwen he greue&eth; &thorn;e mea&slong;t, &amp; toward
&thorn;e wi&eth; fondinge wodeluker weorre&eth;, &yogh;if &thorn;u wel
hile&slong; te under godes wenge&slong;; for, &thorn;urh
&thorn;i&slong; weorre, he &yogh;arke&eth; &thorn;e, un&thorn;onc
hi&slong;e te&eth;, &thorn;e bli&slong;&slong;e &amp; te crune of
cri&slong;tes icorene.  And ihesu cri&slong;t leue &thorn;e,
&thorn;urh his ble&slong;cede nome, &amp; alle &thorn;eo &thorn;at
leauen luue of lami mon, for to beon his leofmon ; &amp; leue
&slong;wa hare heorte halden to him, &thorn;at hare fle&slong;ches
eggunge, ne &thorn;e feondes fondunge, ne nan of his eor&eth;liche
limen, ne weorri hare heorte wit, ne wrenche ham ut of &thorn;e wei
&thorn;at ha beo&eth; in gongen; And helpe ham &slong;wa in him to
hihen toward heuene, a &eth;at ha beon i&slong;tihe &thorn;ider,
a&slong; hare brudlac &slong;chal, in al &thorn;at eauer &slong;el
i&slong;, wi&eth; &thorn;ene &slong;eli brudgume &thorn;at
&slong;ihe&eth; alle &slong;elh&eth;e of, &slong;itten buten ende!
AMEN!
    </P>

